Research Interests

I’m a PhD candidate in Jorge Vivanco’s lab. We research root and rhizosphere biology and ecology. My specific research focuses on how crop domestication and subsequent breeding events shift the strategies plants employ to recover nutrients (specifically phosphorus) from soil.

Influential papers

Right before I began my masters degree, I read the breakthrough paper in phosphorus research, “The story of phosphorus: Global food security and food for thought” (Cordell, Drangert, and White 2009). Here, Cordell et al. outline that global reserves of rock phosphate, from which the phosphorus in fertilizers are mined, is finite. Further, at the current rates of use, the limited supplies remaining for this essential nutrient are not sufficient to sustain life.

Recently, I have been coming back to an article that investigates the divergence of the soil microbiome communities and functions between wild and domesticated beans (Pérez-Jaramillo et al. 2017). This research is headed by Juan Perez-Jaramillo, a leader in the world of wild crop microbiome research (Pérez-Jaramillo, Mendes, and Raaijmakers (2016) Pérez-Jaramillo et al. (2018), Pérez-Jaramillo et al. (2019)).

The mathematics behind my research

As part of my research, I screen many accessions of wild, heirloom, and modern vegetables to understand their differences in phosphorus acquisition. However, because wild varieties are often smaller by nature, it is not valid to compare the raw biomass accumulation of wild to modern accessions. Thus, to accurately compare the effects of low-P stress on my crops, I use a simple calculation to compare the relative effects on my samples.

Relative biomass:

It is easy to write complex mathematics using a mathematical typesetting engine called TeX. Write two displayed equations that are relevant to your work. For a quick primer on TeX and LaTeX you can download this cheatsheet and then fiddle with including things between the double dollar signs below: \[ RDM = \frac{DM_L}{DM_H} \cdot 100 \]

where “DML dry mass in the unfertilized treatment, and “DMH” is dry mass in the fertilized treatment.

We also approximate microbial biomass through qPCR reads:

\[ GeneCPS= \sum_{i=1}^{n_o} \frac{n_i}{N} \cdot \frac{GeneCPGi}{16SCPGi} \cdot 16SCPGs \] where Gene.CPS = functional gene copies g-1 soil FW, Sobs = number of observed Amplicon Sequence Variants (ASV), ni = number of sequenced reads in ASV i, N = number of sequenced reads, Gene.CPGi = functional gene copies per genome for ASV i, 16S.CPGi = 16S rRNA copies per genome for ASV i, 16S.CPS = 16S rRNA copies g-1 soil FW.

My computing experience

I am familiar with R/RStudio. I have limited experience with functions and for loops, but for non-iterative work, I am comfortable working with R.

Here is an example of some code I wrote recently that shows how to plot a dbRDA and evalute significance in b-diversity:

ord <- capscale(dist ~ Fertilization + Domestication/Variety + Fertilization*Domestication/Variety + Variety, data=d)
sppscores(ord) <- data

adonis2(dist ~ Fertilization + Domestication/Variety + Fertilization*Domestication/Variety + Variety, data=d, perm=999, by="terms") 
pair.mod<-pairwise.adonis(dist,factors=d$Variety, p.adjust.m = "fdr")
pair.mod 

ev <- eigenvals(ord)
Axis1_exp = round(ev[1] / sum(ev) * 100, 1)
Axis2_exp = round(ev[2] / sum(ev) * 100, 1)
axes <- as.data.frame(vegan::scores(ord, display="sites", choices=c(1:2)))
names(axes) <- c("Axis1", "Axis2")
axes <- cbind(d, axes) 

axes$Variety <- factor(axes$Variety,level = c('LA0716', 'LA1519', 'LA1580','LA1698','B Pink', 'Marglobe', 'Matchless', 'Rutgers', 'Bobcat', 'Quali T','Line 1','Line 2'))

p<-ggplot(data=axes, aes(x=Axis1, y=Axis2, fill=Variety, shape=Domestication)) +
  geom_point(size=6) +
  stat_ellipse(aes(group=Fertilization, color = Fertilization))+
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = 'Paired')+
  scale_color_manual(values = c('black','grey44'))+
  scale_shape_manual(values=c(21,22,23)) +
  guides(fill = guide_legend(
    override.aes=list(shape = rep(21,2)))) +
  labs(x=paste0('CAP1 (', Axis1_exp, '%)'), 
       y=paste0('CAP2 (', Axis2_exp, '%)')) +
   theme(axis.text=element_text(size=18, colour = "black"), 
        axis.title=element_text(size=32,face="bold"),
        axis.line = element_line(colour = "black"),
        panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
        panel.border = element_blank(),
        panel.background = element_blank(),
        legend.key = element_blank(),
        legend.text = element_text(size = 24),
        legend.title = element_text(size = 24, face = 'bold'));p
ggsave(plot=p, filename = 'Data/Outputs/Figures/SuppFigure1.pdf', width = 14, height = 10)

Evaluating some R code

This graph shows public data about water discharge at a site along the Poudre river.

library(dataRetrieval)
library(dygraphs)
library(xts)
library(tidyverse)
q <- readNWISdv(siteNumbers = '06752260',
                parameterCd = '00060',
                startDate = '2017-01-01',
                endDate = '2022-01-01') %>%
  rename(q = 'X_00060_00003')

q_xts <- xts(q$q, order.by = q$Date)


dygraph(q_xts, main = "Interactive Water Discharge Graph") %>%
  dyAxis("y", label = "Discharge (cfs)")%>% dySeries("V1", strokeWidth = 2, strokePattern = "dashed")
